SINCLAIR LOGISTICS, LLC
LOCAL TARIFF Containing RULES AND REGULATIONS Governing THE TRANSPORTATION of CRUDE PETROLEUM By Pipeline
The Rules and Regulations published in this rules and regulations tariff only apply to tariffs making specific reference by F.E.R.C. number to these Rules and Regulations; these references will include supplements to this tariff and successive issuances of this tariff.
ISSUED: January 24, 2017 EFFECTIVE: January 27, 2017
Issued on 2 days' notice under authority of 18 C.F.R. 341.14. This tariff publication is conditionally accepted subject to refund pending a 30-day review period.
Issued by: Mark A. Petersen President Sinclair Logistics, LLC 550 East South Temple Salt Lake City, UT 84102 mpetersen@SinclairOil.com
TABLE OF CONTENTS
Item/Rule Page Number Abbreviations and Definitions 10 4-6 Additives 260 18 Commodity 30 8 Common Stream Petroleum Connecting Carriers 220 16 Communications Facilities 210 15 Creditworthiness 160 13 Delivery and Demurrage 130 12 Destination Facilities 80 10 Diversion or Reconsignment 100 11 Force Majeure 170 14 Gauging, Deductions and Adjustments 90 10-11 Liability of Carrier 180 15 Linefill 120 12 Mixtures 40 8 Payment of Charges 150 12-13 Pipeage Contracts Required 250 18 Proration Procedures 230 16-17 Quantities 60 9 Rates Applicable 140 12 Required Shipper Information 240 17 Segregation and Variations in Quality and Gravity 70 9-10 Specifications and Restrictions 20 7-8 Storage and Transit 110 11 Tenders 50 8 Time Limitations on Claims 200 15 Title 190 15
GENERAL APPLICATION
The rules and regulations published in this tariff apply only to tariffs that make specific reference by F.E.R.C. number or State Commission number to this Rules and Regulations tariff. The references in those tariffs will include supplements to this tariff and successive issuances of this tariff.
Crude Petroleum will be transported through Carrier's facilities only as provided in this Rules and Regulations tariff, except that specific rules and regulations published in individual tariffs will take precedence over the rules and regulations published here.
RULES AND REGULATIONS
Crude Petroleum will be transported through Carrier's facilities only as provided in these Rules and Regulations.
10. ABBREVIATIONS AND DEFINITIONS
As used in these Rules and Regulations, the following terms have the following meanings:
1.1 "a.m." means a time of day after midnight and before noon Mountain Standard Time.
1.2 "Actual Shipments" means the volumes of Crude Petroleum that originate and are Tendered at a regular Receipt Point during a month. For greater certainty Crude Petroleum re-entering the pipeline at intermediate points will not be considered to be Actual Shipments.
1.3 "Affiliate" means any entity that is under direct or indirect common control, or directly or indirectly: (i) controls a Shipper; (ii) is controlled by another Shipper; (iii) is controlled by the same entity that controls a Shipper; or (iv) is controlled by and through one or more intermediaries that control another Shipper. For the purposes of this definition the term "controls" and "controlled by" shall mean the use of shared mailing or business addresses, the use of shared business telephone numbers, the use of common bank account(s) with regard to the payment of transportation charges, substantially the same management or general partner, the power to direct or cause the direction of the management or any other means, either directly or indirectly, that results in control in fact; but notwithstanding the foregoing includes with respect to the control of or by a corporation the ownership of shares or equity interests carrying not less than fifty (50%) percent of the voting rights regardless of whether such ownership occurs directly or indirectly.
1.4 "Allocated Tender" means the volume allocated by Carrier to a Shipper that has Tendered Crude Petroleum to Carrier. The Allocated Tender to each Shipper will be determined by the provisions of Item 230 of this Tariff.
1.5 "API" refers to the American Petroleum Institute.
1.6 "Applicable Law" means all laws; statutes; directives; codes; ordinances; rules; regulations; municipal by-laws; judicial, arbitral, administrative, ministerial, departmental or regulatory judgments, orders, decisions, rulings or awards; consent orders; consent decrees; and policies of any Governmental Authority, applicable to common carrier oil pipelines, generally, or the pipeline operated by Carrier.
1.7 "ASTM" refers to ASTM International formerly known as American Society for Testing and Materials.
1.8 "Average Monthly Volume" means the average of a Historic Shipper's Actual Shipments of Crude Petroleum with respect to the line segment or segments calculated in accordance with Item 230.
1.9 "Barrel" means forty-two (42) United States gallons at sixty degrees (60?) Fahrenheit and zero (0) gauge pressure if the vapor pressure of the Crude Petroleum is at or below atmospheric pressure, or at equilibrium pressure if the vapor pressure of the Crude Petroleum is above atmospheric pressure.
1.10 "Bpd" means Barrels per day.
1.11 "Carrier" means and refers to Sinclair Logistics, LLC ("Sinclair" or "Sinclair Logistics").
1.12 "Consignee" means the Shipper or a party whom a Shipper has designated as the recipient of a delivery of Crude Petroleum.
1.13 "Crude Petroleum" means the direct product of oil wells or a mixture of the indirect products transportable like the direct products and containing not more than two percent (2%) of sediment, water and other impurities.
1.14 "Delivery Point" means any of the points identified on Carrier's currently effective FERC tariff as a location to which products are discharged from the pipeline. These points are generally designated under the "To" point listing on the applicable rate schedules.
1.15 "FERC" or "the Commission" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, or any successor Governmental Authority.
1.16 "Force Majeure" or "Force Majeure Event" means the events or occurrences referred to in Item 170.
1.17 "Governmental Authority" means any governmental, administrative or regulatory entity, tribal authority, commission, board, agency, instrumentality, bureau or political subdivision, and any court, tribunal or judicial or arbitral body (whether national, federal, state or local or, in the case of an arbitral body, whether governmental, public or private), having jurisdiction over Carrier.
1.18 "Guernsey Tank" means and refers to the tank Carrier has leased at Guernsey, Wyoming to facilitate common stream operations under Items 20 and 70(e) of this Tariff.
1.19 "Linefill" means the static quantity of Crude Petroleum, including working stock needed to occupy the physical space within the pipeline and any applicable facilities, all as set forth in Carrier's Rules and Regulations.
1.20 "Net Balance" means the net balance of volumes Tendered to Carrier for transportation, calculated pursuant to Carrier's Rules and Regulations Tariff.
1.21 "No." means number.
1.22 "Non-Performance Penalty" means an amount equal to the product of the applicable tariff multiplied by the difference between the Shipper's Allocated Tender and its actual shipment of Crude Petroleum in the month of Prorationing under Item 230.
1.23 "p.m." means a time of day after noon and before midnight Mountain Standard Time.
1.24 "Person" means an individual, partnership, limited liability company, corporation, trust, estate, unincorporated association, nominee, joint venture, or other entity.
1.25 "Receipt Point" means any point listed on Carrier's currently effective FERC tariff as a location at which Crude Petroleum is Tendered to Carrier for delivery to a Delivery Point. These points are generally designated as "From" on applicable rate schedules.
1.26 "Shipper" means a Person that Tenders Crude Petroleum to Carrier for transportation from a specified Receipt Point to a specified Delivery Point in accordance with Carrier's Rules and Regulations.
1.27 "Tariff" means Carrier's FERC Rate Schedules and Rules and Regulations tariff as filed with the FERC and any subsequently filed version thereof.
1.28 "Tender" means an offer by a Shipper to Carrier of a stated quantity of Crude Petroleum for transportation from a specified Receipt Point to a specified Delivery Point in accordance with Carrier's Rules and Regulations.
20. SPECIFICATIONS AND RESTRICTIONS OF PETROLEUM APPLICABLE TO COMMON STREAM SHIPMENTS
Carrier reserves the right to reject all Tenders of Crude Petroleum for common stream shipments when, in Carrier's sole determination:
(a) The Reid vapor pressure of the Crude Petroleum, or any mixture thereof with indirect products, exceeds twelve (12) pounds at one hundred (100?) degrees Fahrenheit;
(b) The true vapor pressure of the Crude Petroleum, or any mixture thereof with indirect products, might result in Carrier's noncompliance with Federal, State, or Local governmental requirements regarding hydrocarbon emissions;
(c) The Crude Petroleum contains impurities exceeding five-tenths of one percent (0.50%) including not more than two-tenths of one percent (0.20%) water; (d) The sulfur content of any Crude Petroleum offered or received exceeds two-tenths of one percent (0.20%) by weight; (e) The API Gravity of the Crude Petroleum does not fall between forty (40) and forty-six (46) degrees;
(f) The Crude Petroleum has been partially refined; or
(g) The Crude Petroleum has been contaminated by the presence of any chemicals including, but not limited to, chlorinated and/or oxygenated hydrocarbons and lead.
The Crude Petroleum transported by Carrier shall not contain sand, dust, dirt, gums, impurities or other objectionable substances that may interfere with the transportation of Crude Petroleum.
If Carrier determines that a Shipper does not comply with the specification provisions of this tariff, Carrier may, at its discretion and in a non-discriminatory manner, require such Shipper, at Shipper's sole cost and expense, to remove its Crude Petroleum from Carrier's facilities as directed by Carrier. Carrier may take such further action and remedies as it deems appropriate to lessen or mitigate any adverse impacts to Carrier's facilities.
Crude Petroleum delivered to Carrier's facilities that does not meet these specifications shall be considered contaminated. If upon investigation Carrier determines that a Shipper has delivered to Carrier's facilities contaminated Crude Petroleum, Carrier may, at its discretion and in a non-discriminatory manner, exclude such Shipper from further entry into applicable segments of the System until such time as quality specifications are met. Shipper will be required to provide Carrier with written assurances that such abuses will not recur. Shippers who have violated these Common Stream restrictions may be liable for damages to other Shippers in the same Common Stream.
If a Shipper fails to remove its Crude Petroleum from Carrier's facilities in accordance with Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs, Carrier, in addition to any other remedy it may have under the Tariff, at law or in equity, shall have the right to remove and sell such Crude Petroleum in a lawful manner as deemed appropriate by Carrier. Carrier shall pay from the proceeds of such sale all costs incurred by Carrier with respect to the storage, removal and sale of such Crude Petroleum and Carrier shall be entitled to retain a reasonable estimate of any damages, costs, and expenses already incurred or anticipated to be incurred by Carrier in respect of such Crude Petroleum. The remainder of such proceeds, if any, shall be paid by Carrier to the Shipper or in accordance with the Shipper's direction. Carrier may take such further action and remedies as it deems appropriate to lessen or mitigate any adverse impacts to Carrier's facilities caused by Shipper's failure to comply with this provision.
30. MIXTURES
The indirect liquid products of oil or gas wells, including gasoline and liquefied petroleum gases (but excluding condensate), hereinafter referred to as indirect products, will not be accepted or transported as a mixture with the direct liquid products of oil wells, hereinafter referred to as direct products.
40. COMMODITY
Carrier is engaged in the transportation of Crude Petroleum by pipeline and will not accept any indirect products of oil and gas wells, mixtures containing indirect products or other commodities for transportation.
50. TENDERS
(a) Crude Petroleum will be transported only under a Tender accepted by Carrier, from Receipt Points (or from facilities connected to Carrier's gathering system when gathering service is to be performed by Carrier) to Delivery Points when a tariff covering the movement is lawfully in effect and on file with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, and with the appropriate state commission covering intrastate traffic.
(b) Any Shipper desiring to Tender Crude Petroleum for transportation shall make such Tender to Carrier in writing on or before the twenty-fifth (25th) day of the month preceding the month during which the transportation under the Tender is to begin. Unless such notification is made, Carrier will be under no obligation to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation. However, if operating conditions permit and at the sole discretion of Carrier, Tenders for Crude Petroleum may be accepted for transportation after the twenty-fifth (25th) day of the month preceding the month during which the transportation under the Tender is to begin.
60. QUANTITIES
(a) A Tender will be accepted only when the total quantity covered by such Tender will be made available for transportation within the month when the Tender is to begin.
(b) Any quantity of Crude Petroleum will be accepted from lease tanks or other facilities to which Carrier is connected, if such quantity can be so consolidated with other Crude Petroleum so that Carrier can make delivery of not less than ten thousand (10,000) barrels during the month.
70. SEGREGATION AND VARIATIONS IN QUALITY AND GRAVITY
The following rules and regulations apply to the shipment of Crude Petroleum:
(a) As part of its common stream transportation, Carrier may, at its discretion and in a non-discriminatory manner, reject any Crude Petroleum tendered for common stream transportation that does not meet the quality criteria of the common stream as established by Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs. Carrier will take appropriate and reasonable steps to monitor the quality of its common streams and to investigate suspected abuses of common stream criteria violations. Monitoring of common streams will include gravity and sulfur testing and may include simulated distillation and other testing to determine quality.
(b) If abuses of the common stream quality are determined, the Shipper causing such abuses shall be advised to cease and desist all such actions. Failure to desist or failure to cooperate in ending such practices shall result in that Shipper being barred from shipping in the common stream where such abuses occurred. Before such Shipper is permitted to regain its Shipper status in the common stream, the Shipper will be required to provide Carrier with written assurances that such abuses will not recur.
(c) Carrier will work with connecting carriers regarding Carrier's quality issues and will advise such connecting carriers that any Crude Petroleum found to be a detriment to Carrier's common stream may be rejected for further transportation on Carrier's system.
(d) Since variations in gravity and/or quality of common stream Crude Petroleum are inherent in common stream operations, Carrier will not be liable for such variations occurring while Crude Petroleum is in its custody, nor is Carrier under any obligation to deliver the identical Crude Petroleum received, but will make delivery out of such common stream.
(e) Carrier's tank at Guernsey, Wyoming is for common stream deliveries only. All deliveries to the Guernsey Tank must meet the quality specifications listed in Item 20 of this tariff.
(f) When requested by a Shipper, and if operationally feasible in the sole determination of Carrier, Carrier, at its discretion and in a non-discriminatory manner, will endeavor to segregate Crude Petroleum of a kind and/or quality that does not meet the quality specifications listed in Item 20. Carrier, using commercially reasonable efforts and in accordance with Paragraph (g) of this Item 70, will make delivery at Delivery Points of such Crude Petroleum that is substantially similar in kind and/or quality to the Crude Petroleum Tendered to Carrier at the Receipt Point. For such segregated batches, Shipper must provide Crude Petroleum in such quantities (see Note 1) and at such specified times as may be necessary to permit such segregated movements via Carrier's facilities. Carrier will not be liable for failure to deliver the identical Crude Petroleum or for any variations in the gravity and/or quality of Crude Petroleum occurring while such segregated crude is in Carrier's custody.
(g) Carrier does not provide tanks for segregated Crude Petroleum batches and Shipper must provide destination facilities at Guernsey, Wyoming for the delivery of segregated Crude Petroleum batches. Carrier assumes no responsibility to accept any Tender of segregated Crude Petroleum batches from any Shipper or Consignee that does not have facilities for promptly receiving such segregated Crude Petroleum batches at the Delivery Point. Carrier has no obligation to accept segregated Crude Petroleum batches for transportation with a sulfur content of one-half of one percent (.50%) or greater and/or API Gravity that does not fall between thirty-five (35) and fifty (50) degrees.
Note 1: The quantity of Crude Petroleum to be accepted and transported under the provisions of this paragraph will be determined by Carrier in accordance with current operations through its existing facilities involved in the segregated movements, but in no event shall the quantity for a single delivery be less than the minimum quantity specified in Item 60.
80. DESIGNATION FACILITIES
No duty to transport will arise until evidence satisfactory to Carrier has been furnished that consignee has provided necessary facilities to which Carrier is connected and has made necessary arrangements for accepting delivery of shipments promptly on arrival at the destination. Carrier does not provide truck or rail unloading facilities as part of its transportation service.
90. GAUGING, DEDUCTIONS AND ADJUSTMENTS
(a) All shipments Tendered to Carrier for transportation shall be gauged or metered and tested by a representative of Carrier or by automatic equipment approved by Carrier prior to, or at the same time as, receipt from the Shipper. Shipper or Consignee shall have the privilege of being present or represented during the gauging or metering and testing. Shipper will grant access to Shipper's facility to Carrier's representative for witnessing meter or gauge readings or meter proving and for any other required inspection incidental to measurement and transportation of Crude Petroleum. Quantities gauged or metered shall be corrected from observed temperatures to sixty degrees (60?) Fahrenheit using applicable Standard Petroleum Measurement Tables adopted jointly by the American Petroleum Institute (API Standard 2540) and the American Society for Testing Materials (ASTM Standard D 1250).
(b) Shipper will pay to Carrier a fee equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the volume of Crude Petroleum shipped multiplied by the difference between the monthly weighted average WTI price of Crude Petroleum less the monthly weighted average of the Light Sweet Guernsey trade differential as published by Net Energy in the US Monthly Index to account for inherent losses, including but not limited to shrinkage, evaporation, interface losses, normal "over and short" losses, and other normal losses during transportation with losses being assessed only upon delivery at the Destination Point on Carrier's mainline.
(c) The net quantities as determined under paragraph (a) will be the amounts accountable at destination.
100. DIVERSION OR RECONSIGNMENT
Crude Petroleum in transport may be diverted without an additional charge to a Delivery Point other than that originally specified on the Tender, or Crude Petroleum in transport may be reconsigned without an additional charge to another Shipper at a Delivery Point only if such diversion or reconsignment is made in writing by the Shipper of record prior to delivery at the originally designated Delivery Point and when such diversion or reconsignment will not adversely affect pipeline operations. Any such diversion will be permitted only in accordance with and subject to Carrier's rates, Rules and Regulations and Tariffs applicable from point of origin to point of final destination and, upon condition that no out of line or backhaul movement will be made.
110. STORAGE AND TRANSIT
(a) Carrier has a working tank required for the transportation of Crude Petroleum in the common stream but does not offer other tanks as part of the service specified in these Rules and Regulations. Carrier does not offer facilities for rendering, nor does it offer storage service. Provisions for storage in transit in facilities furnished by Shipper at points on Carrier's system will be permitted to the extent authorized under individual transit tariffs lawfully on file with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
(b) Each Shipper will be required to furnish Crude Petroleum into inventory for its proportionate share of the linefill in such amount as deemed necessary by Carrier.
120. LINEFILL
Prior to the delivery of Crude Petroleum from Carrier's system, each Shipper will be required to supply a pro rata share of the volume of Crude Petroleum necessary for pipeline and tankage fill and reasonable additional minimum quantities required to ensure efficient operation of Carrier's pipeline system. Each Shipper will retain title to the linefill it provides to Carrier. Crude Petroleum provided by Shipper for this purpose may be withdrawn from the pipeline system only with the prior approval of Carrier, with such approval not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed, or after reasonable notice has been provided to Carrier of Shipper's intention to discontinue shipment in the pipeline system, not to exceed sixty (60) days. Carrier will not be liable for failure to deliver the identical Crude Petroleum or for any variations in the gravity and/or quality of Crude Petroleum occurring while such Crude Petroleum is in Carrier's custody.
130. DELIVERY AND DEMURRAGE
(a) Carrier will transport and deliver Crude Petroleum with reasonable diligence and dispatch, but will not accept Crude Petroleum to be transported in time for any particular market.
(b) After any shipment has had time to arrive at destination, and on twenty-four (24) hours notice to Consignee, Carrier may begin delivery at its current rate of pumping.
(c) Commencing after the first seven (7) o'clock a.m., five (5) days after expiration of said notice, a demurrage charge of five cents ($0.05) per barrel per day of twenty-four (24) hours shall accrue on any part of said shipment offered for delivery and not taken as prescribed in paragraph (b) of this Item. After the expiration of said notice, Carrier's liability for loss, damage, or delay shall be that of a warehouseman only.
140. RATES APPLICABLE
Crude Petroleum transported shall be subject to the rates in effect on the dates such Crude Petroleum is received by Carrier irrespective of the date of Tender.
150. PAYMENT OF CHARGES
(a) Carrier shall invoice Shipping no later than the seventh (7th) day of the month for the preceding month and Shipper shall remit payment to Carrier no later than five (5) business days following receipt of Carrier's invoice. Shipper shall be responsible for payment of transportation and all other charges applicable to the shipment according to the provisions of Carrier's rates, Rules and Regulations and Tariffs and if required, shall prepay such charges or furnish guaranty of payment satisfactory to Carrier. Carrier will have a lien on all Crude Petroleum accepted for transportation to secure the payment of all charges, including demurrage charges, and may, at Carrier's discretion and in a non-discriminatory manner, refuse to deliver Crude Petroleum until all charges have been paid.
(b) If said charges or any part thereof shall remain unpaid five (5) days after the invoice due date, computed from the first seven (7) o'clock a.m. after notice is furnished in writing to Shipper of intention to enforce Carrier's lien as herein provided, or when there shall be failure to take the Crude Petroleum at the point of destination as provided in Item 130 within five (5) days, computed from the first seven (7) o'clock a.m. after expiration of the notice therein provided, Carrier shall have the right, either itself or through an agent, to sell said Crude Petroleum for cash. Notice of the sale shall be furnished twenty-four (24) hours in advance to Shipper in a reasonable manner.
(c) Carrier may be a bidder and purchaser at such sale. Out of the proceeds of said sale Carrier may pay itself all transportation, demurrage, and other lawful charges, expense of notice, advertisement, sale, and other necessary expense, and of caring for and maintaining the Crude Petroleum, and the balance shall be held for whomsoever may be lawfully entitled thereto.
160. CREDITWORTHINESS
(a) Carrier shall not be required to provide service to any Shipper who fails to meet Carrier's standards for creditworthiness. In this regard Carrier may require that a Shipper provide audited financial statements to Carrier within ninety (90) days of its fiscal year end for review by Carrier. Carrier may also require a Shipper to provide unaudited interim financial statements.
(b) Carrier shall not be required to perform and shall have the ability to suspend service for any Shipper who is or has become insolvent, fails to demonstrate creditworthiness under paragraph (a) of this Item, fails to timely provide information to Carrier as requested in paragraph (a) of this Item, or fails to demonstrate ongoing creditworthiness through the credit information referred to in paragraph (a) of this Item. Accordingly, Carrier may suspend service to any Shipper who fails to meet creditworthiness requirements unless the Shipper provides one of the following forms of Performance Assurance:
i. an irrevocable letter of credit with terms and amounts acceptable to Carrier in its sole discretion and from a bank acceptable to Carrier in its sole discretion;
ii. a guaranty with terms acceptable to Carrier in its sole discretion and executed by a guarantor acceptable to Carrier in its sole discretion;
iii. such other form of credit security acceptable to Carrier in its sole discretion; or
iv. prepayment at least ten (10) calendar days prior to the first day of a month of an amount of money reasonably calculated by Carrier to cover any payments for transportation services likely to be incurred by Shipper during such month.
170. FORCE MAJEURE
The term "Event of Force Majeure" shall mean any event or occurrence beyond the reasonable control of a Party which by the exercise of due diligence and reasonable care such Party is unable to prevent or overcome that delays or prevents such Party from performing any of its obligations as a shipper or carrier under the provisions of Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs, including the following: (a) natural phenomena and acts of God such as storms, floods, fires, lightning, freezes, landslides, hurricanes, extreme heat, washouts, and earthquakes; (b) strikes, lockouts, boycotts, picketing, labor or other industrial disturbance; (c) acts of public enemy, wars, terrorist acts, blockages, insurrections, civil disturbances or riots; (d) the order of any Governmental Authority; (e) explosions, breakage, accidental damage to lines of pipe, machinery, equipment or storage tanks.
Events of Force Majeure include events of force majeure declared by a third party that interfere with performance under the terms of Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs, provided that such events of force majeure would otherwise qualify as an Event of Force Majeure under Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs.
Events of Force Majeure shall not include any of the following acts or events: (i) changes in costs of materials or Crude Petroleum; (ii) a Party's inability to economically perform its obligations under the provisions of Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs, including a Party's inability or failure to pay amounts owed; (iii) Shipper being unable to deliver Crude Petroleum to Carrier for shipment hereunder at an Origin Point or receive Crude Petroleum at a Delivery Point due to the failure or inability of any connecting carrier or gathering pipeline system (other than those owned or operated by Carrier or its Affiliates) to deliver or accept such Crude Petroleum, whether due to Force Majeure or otherwise; (iv) with respect to Shipper, loss of or failure of crude oil supply, reservoirs or wells, or production declines.
Notice: If the Event of Force Majeure renders either Party unable, in whole or in part, to carry out any of its obligations under the provisions of Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs, such Party (the "Notifying Party") must give the other Party (the "Noticed Party") notice and a full detailed explanation in writing as soon as practicable after the occurrence of the causes relied upon, or give initial notice by telephone or e-mail and follow such notice with a written confirmation within forty-eight (48) hours after the occurrence of the Event of Force Majeure.
Obligations: The Notifying Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to: (i) correct the events or conditions resulting in the Event of Force Majeure; (ii) resume the continuation of its performance under Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs; and (iii) minimize the impact of such Event of Force Majeure on the Noticed Party.
180. LIABILITY OF CARRIER
(a) Carrier, while in possession of any Crude Petroleum, will not be liable for any loss thereof, or damage thereto, or delay, caused by an act of God, the public enemy, quarantine, the authority of law, or of public authority, strikes, riots insurrection, inherent nature of the goods, or the act or default of the Shipper consignee, except as may be otherwise provided in Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs.
(b) In case of loss or damage from causes other than the sole negligence of Carrier, such loss or damage shall be charged will be charged proportionately to each shipper in the ratio that its Crude Petroleum, or portion thereof, received and undelivered at the time the loss occurs, bears to the total of all Crude Petroleum then in the custody of Carrier for transportation via the lines or other facilities in which the loss occurs; and Carrier will be obligated to deliver only that portion of such Crude Petroleum remaining after deducting Shipper's proportion of such loss determined as aforesaid. Transportation charges will be assessed only on the quantity delivered.
190. TITLE
A Tender of Crude Petroleum shall be deemed a warranty of title by the party Tendering, but acceptance shall not be deemed a representation by Carrier as to title. Carrier may, in the absence of adequate security, decline to receive any Crude Petroleum that is subject to litigation involving a dispute over title, or which is encumbered by any lien of which Carrier has notice.
200. TIME LIMITATIONS ON CLAIMS
As a condition precedent to recovery for loss, damage, or delay to shipments, claims must be filed in writing with Carrier within nine (9) months and one (1) day after reasonable time for delivery, based on Carrier's normal operations; and suits shall be instituted against Carrier only within two (2) years and one (1) day from the day when notice in writing is given by Carrier to the claimant that Carrier has disallowed the claim or any part or parts thereof specified in the notice. Where claims are not filed or suits are not instituted thereon in accordance with the foregoing provisions, Carrier will not be liable, and such claims will not be paid.
210. COMMUNICATIONS FACILITIES
Shippers may use Carrier's private communication facilities without additional charge for messages incident to their shipments. Carrier will not be liable for non-delivery of messages, or for errors or delays in transmission or interruption of the service.
220. COMMON STREAM PETROLEUM CONNECTING CARRIERS
When both receipts from and deliveries to a connecting carrier of substantially the same grade of Crude Petroleum are scheduled at the same interconnection, Carrier reserves the right, with the cooperation of the connecting carrier, to offset like volumes of common stream Crude Petroleum in order to avoid the unnecessary use of energy which would be required to physically pump the offsetting volumes. Carrier will apply to such offsetting of volumes the applicable tariff rate. When this rate is exercised, Carrier will make further deliveries for the Shipper involved from its common stream Crude Petroleum.
230. PRORATION PROCEDURES
For purposes of this Item 230, the following terms shall mean:
"Historic Shipper" refers to a Shipper that has shipped Crude Petroleum on the pipeline in each of the six (6) months prior to the month of allocation.
"New Shipper" is any Shipper that does not meet the qualifications of a Historic Shipper.
"Non-Performance Penalty" means an amount equal to the product of the applicable tariff multiplied by the difference between the Shipper's Allocated Tender and its actual shipment of Crude Petroleum in the month of Prorationing under this Item 230.
When more Crude Petroleum is tendered for transportation in a month on a line segment than Carrier can transport, Carrier shall apportion its capacity by allocating space in the line in the following manner:
Before allocations are made to Historic Shippers, ten percent (10%) of Carrier's total capacity will be reserved for New Shippers. The remaining capacity shall be allocated among Historic Shippers in proportion to their respective Average Monthly Volumes.
(a) The Average Monthly Volumes of each Shipper will be calculated on the basis of the Actual Shipments made by that Shipper in the six (6) month period beginning six (6) months prior to the month of allocation.
The ten percent (10%) of Carrier total capacity reserved for New Shippers shall be allocated as follows:
(b) If less than four (4) New Shippers have submitted nominations for the affected line segment, each New Shipper will be allocated the lesser of either two and one half percent (2.5%) of Carrier's total Capacity or its nominated volume. In the event that more than four (4) New Shippers have submitted nominations for the affected line segment, the nominated volumes for each New Shipper shall be totaled and divided into the ten percent (10%) of total Carrier capacity reserved for new Shippers. The resulting percentage shall be the initial New Shipper's proration factor. Each New Shipper will be allocated pipeline segment capacity equal to the lesser of:
i. two and one half percent (2.5%) of Available Capacity;
ii. its nominated volumes; or
iii. its nominated volumes multiplied by the initial New Shipper proration factor.
After New Shipper allocations are made, the remaining capacity shall be allocated among Historic Shippers in proportion to their respective Average Monthly Volumes. If additional capacity is left after capacity is allocated to Historic Shippers under this provision then the remaining capacity will be allocated to New Shippers in proportion to their New Shipper proration factor.
No individual Shipper nomination beyond the physical capacity of the pipeline segments on which the nominated Crude Petroleum will be transported shall be considered. Nominations in excess of these limits will be reduced to Carrier's capacity.
In months of prorationing, all Tenders by shippers shall have the Non-Performance Penalty applied to any shortfall in Tenders of Crude Petroleum from a Shipper that exceeds five percent (5%) of that Shipper's allocated volume. However, the Non-Performance Penalty will not be applied to that portion of shortfalls caused by Force Majeure events. Any Shipper subject to the Non-Performance Penalty and this Item 230 shall remit that Non-Performance Penalty to Carrier within fifteen (15) days of the last day of the month in which the Non-Performance Penalty was incurred. In addition, If a Shipper is subject to the Non-Performance Penalty, the nomination that will be accepted by Carrier from that Shipper in the next three (3) months, beginning two (2) months after the month of non-performance, will be limited to no more than the volume that the Shipper actually shipped during the months of prorationing, provided that this volume limitation will only be applied when the pipeline is being prorationed.
240. REQUIRED SHIPPER INFORMATION
(a) At any time, upon written request of Carrier, on a non-discriminatory basis, any prospective or existing Shipper shall provide to Carrier information that will enable Carrier to enforce Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs. Such information may include, but is not limited to, the names of any Affiliates of the Shipper or prospective Shipper, the legal business name of the Shipper or prospective Shipper and the registered business address of the Shipper or prospective Shipper.
(b) Carrier shall not be obliged to accept Crude Petroleum for transportation from an existing or prospective Shipper if the Shipper or prospective Shipper fails to provide to Carrier any information requested in accordance with paragraph (a) of this Item within ten (10) days of Carrier's written request, or if Carrier reasonably determines that any of the information provided pursuant to paragraph (a) of this Item is false.
250. PIPEAGE CONTRACTS REQUIRED
Separate contracts, in accordance with Carrier's Rules and Regulations and applicable Tariffs, covering facilities, rights of way, actual connection to Carrier, and other details, may be required by Carrier before any duty for transportation shall arise.
260. ADDITIVES
Carrier reserves the right to require, approve, limit or reject the injection of all corrosion inhibitors, viscosity or pour point depressants, drag reducing agents or other such additives in the Crude Petroleum to be transported before such Crude Petroleum will be accepted for transportation and may restrict Delivery of Crude Petroleum to destination points based on the actual concentration of such additives upon delivery.
